@node "LoadArc" "Loading an Archive"
@prev "BBFunctions"
@next "CloseArc"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Load an Archive@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 To  load  an archive and actually enter the management functions you have to
 select  this  menu  item.   A standard (ASL) file requester will present you
 with the list of available archives.

 For  simplicity  reasons,  the  list  is filtered and only shows files whose
 names end in '.bb3', which is the normal extension of BancaBase's archives.

 If  you  choose  an incorrect archive or a file whose format is unrecognized
 you will get a proper error message.

 If the chosen archive was protected with a password you will be prompted for
 it  by  a requester.  The program will only actually load the archive if the
 typed password is correct, and deny the access otherwise.

 Opening  an  archive will cause the program to load all the related files as
 well, like graphic preferences, function keys, lists etc.

 Once the loading process is completed you will be presented with the @{"Main Menu" link "MainMenu" 0}.


 NOTE:   If  the program finds a GUI-preferences file (.prefs) related to the
 archive  being  loaded,  it  loads  that  as well and performs all necessary
 adjustments  to assume the new graphical appearance.  To do that it may need
 to  close  the  main  screen:  this  is  a  perfectly  normal  and necessary
 behaviour.
@endnode

@node "CloseArc" "Closing an Archive"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Close Archive@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 Select  this  function  to close the archive currently in use and go back to
 the @{"Archive Management Menu" link "ArchiveMenu" 0}.
@endnode

@node "CreaArc" "Create a new Archive"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Create new Archive@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 You have to select this function if you need to create a new archive.  These
 parameters can be configured :

o @{b}Archive Filename@{ub}
  The  name of the actual file where all archive-related data will be stored.
  The name must include the path  and  end  in  '.bb3',  but the program will
  automatically  add  this extension in case you forgot it.  You must not use
  characters  like space, # and the rest of DOS special characters.  To avoid
  mistakes  you  can  activate the POP-UP gadget (next to this string gadget)
  which  opens an ASL File-requester.  Then select the complete path and type
  in the 'File' field the archive name only.

o @{b}Archive Description@{ub}
  A string which represents the 'title' you wish assign to your archive.  Any
  character conbination is allowed here.

o @{b}Protected by Password@{ub}
  Click  on  this  gadget  if  you  wish to protect the archive from unwanted
  access.  That  will  bring up a window with two string gadgets, in which to
  enter your  desired  password.   During  the  input  the  characters  typed
  are  not  echoed.  To  avoid  entering  a wrong password, you have to enter
  it twice: the  program  will  continue  only  if it detects  no  difference
  between the two inputs.

  @{u}DON'T FORGET THE PASSWORD !@{uu}
  If  you forget the password there is no way of getting it back.  So try not
  to use unusual symbols of characters, better choose names which are easy to
  remember.   Also  pay  attention  to capital letters:  the password is case
  sensitive.

  If  you  change  your  mind  and don't want to password-protect the archive
  anymore simply re-select the same gadget.  This will remove the password.

o @{b}Date Format@{ub}
  This  section  allows  to  choose  between  the two available date formats.
  DD-MM-YYYY  stands for two digits for the day, two digits for the month and
  four  digits  for the year.  MM-DD-YYYY is the same, but the month is shown
  before the day.

  The  Numerical  Format  allows  switching  between  fixed point and integer
  numbers.   Fixed  point  numbers were introduced to make the program usable
  with foreign currencies, since with Italian Liras you only need integers.

o @{b}Currency/Max withdraw@{ub}
  You can enter the name of your desired currency into the 'currency'  field.
  This  field  has a limit of four characters, but this is enough to indicate
  the  symbol  of currency used in the archive.  For example you can enter DM
  for German marks, Ł.  for British pounds or Lire for Italian Liras.

  BNK  and CDC Max limits indicate the Bank Card and Credit Card settings.  A
  window  is  opened  with  four  fields in it, two for Bank Card and two for
  Credit  Card.   The  Bank  Card  String is the string the program uses as a
  search  key  to  locate  all  operations  made  with Bank Card.  Obviously,
  whenever  you  enter  a Bank Card operation in the archive you have to type
  this identification  string into the 'Description' field.  The 'Max monthly
  withdraw' field is used to set the maximum amount you can withdraw  whithin
  a month.  This  allows the program to calculate the monthly residual credit.
  The two remaining fields behave exactly the same but refer to Credit Card.

o @{b}Other Options@{ub}
  This  gadget  opens  another  window,  where  you  can define the following
  settings:

  @{b}Show total/filtered balance@{ub}
  Enables/disables  the  constant  visualization of balance into the frame at
  the bottom of the screen.  If ticked the balance is shown.

  @{b}Auto recalculation@{ub}
  If  activated the program automatically recalculates both the total and the
  filtered balance whenever an operation which could modify them is performed.
  Obviously,  activating  it  without enabling 'Show total' as well is pretty
  useless.

  @{b}Record viewing colors@{ub}
  You  can  choose the colors used to display records.  At the moment you can
  use  separate  colors  for three kinds of record:  those containing INCOMES
  (with  the + sign), EXPENSES (with - sign) and the remaining records (those
  without  sign).   This  allows  easy  location  of operations in the Record
  Browser.

o @{b}Save Archive@{ub}
  Saves  data  on  disk.   If  the  archive  being saved is a NEW archive the
  program  checks  whether another archive with the same name is present.  If
  this is the case you will be asked to change the archive file name.

  If  otherwise the newly set parameters refer to an already existing archive
  currently in use the program will perform the required updates.

o @{b}Cancel@{ub}
  Exit the configuration window without modifying any setting.
@endnode

@node "DeleteArc" "Delete an Archive"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Delete an Archive@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 Select  this  option  when you wish to remove an archive and all its related
 files from disk.

 Select  the  archive file '.bb3' you want to delete from the file requester.
 If  it's  a  password-protected  archive, you will be asked for the password
 before going on.

 If you confirm all requests the program presents you with before proceeding,
 then  ALL  files  related  to  the  archive  (included) will be definitively
 removed from the disk.

 If an archive is removed by this funcion there is no way of recovering it.
@endnode

@node "RefDate" "Data di Riferimento"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Reference date@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 The  reference  date  is used as a default whenever the user is requested to
 enter a date.

 For  example,  in  the  Insert Operation window the suggested date is copied
 from  the  reference  date.   So  if you need to insert many operations, all
 referring  to  the same date, it's much more convenient to set the reference
 date once than to adjust many times the suggested one.

 For further details see also the @{"Insert Operation" link "InsertRec" 0} function.
@endnode

@node "ScreenBar" "Screen Bar"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Screen Bar@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 Indicates the status of the screen bar. If selected, the original screen bar
 is shown, with visible depth  gadget;  otherwise  it is hidden by the active
 window's title.  There is only an aesthetic difference, this setting doesn't
 affect program functionality.

 You can also set a default value for screen bar status using @{"Icon Tooltypes" link "IconTools" 0}.
@endnode

@node "PublicScreen" "Public Screen"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Public Screen@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This function opens a requester  showing  BancaBase's  public  screen  name,
 which is normally set to:

                         @{b}BancaBase_Screen@{ub}

 If you want to have any application (which must support Public Screens) open
 on  BancaBase's  screen,  you have to pass that string to it as a parameter.
 Normally that parameter is named PUBLIC_SCREEN.

@endnode

@node "UserInfo" "About User"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}About User@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  option  is only available if the program is correctly registered to an
 user.   It  opens  a  window  showing  some  info  about  the user, such  as
 registration  CODE,  registration  date,  first  name,  surname  and city of
 living.

@endnode

@node "LanguageInfo" "About Language"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}About Language@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 Shows some information about the language the program is currently using.

 English  strings  are  built-in:   they  are used whenever the program can't
 locate  the catalog file of your own preferred language, as set in Workbench
 preferences, or when it is unable to load the locale.library.

 You can also 'force' the language the program is going to use by setting the
 @{b}LANGUAGE=@{ub}  Tooltype  in the program icon accordingly.  If you do so
 the  language  you  indicate will be loaded (if present) and used instead of
 the  default  one.   For  further  details  see  @{"Icon Tooltypes" link "IconTools"}.

 This requester shows the  language name, its version and revision number and
 the catalog file author's name.

 It has been introduced to induce the world's catalog translator to translate
 this program's catalog into their own language.

 That's  because  by  doing  so  everybody  can  enjoy his/her name into this
 requester!  :-)

 In order to avoid confusion I'm asking possible translators to send me their
 translations  first.  They  will  be  tested  and  included  into  program's
 distribution archive.
@endnode

@node "ProgramInfo" "About Program"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}About Program@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  window presents you with the BancaBase LOGO and some other information
 such as:

 The complete program version

 Compilation date and time

 Author's @{"Copyright" link "BBCopyRights" 0} data.

 In  the bottom part is explicitly stated if the program is in its registered
 version (thus not cedible), or it's a DEMO (or evalutation) version which is
 freely distributable.

 In the central part of the window a scrolling text field displays registered
 user's  personal  data,  or  a  string  indicating that you are using a DEMO
 version.

@endnode

@node "Iconify" "Iconify"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Iconify@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 Reduces the running program to an icon on the Workbench  screen.  Useful  to
 free  precious graphic (and fast) memory without quitting the program if you
 need to run other programs but don't have enough memory left.

 The icon which appears on Workbench will be the same as the one you normally
 use to run the program.

 To  go back to the program just double click on the newly created icon:  the
 program  will  resume  it's execution showing the same menu it showed before
 being iconified.

@endnode

@node "Quit" "Exit"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Exit@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  program  quits  the  program directly (after asking for confirmation),
 without having to go back to some other menu.

 All open files are closed and all temporary files removed.

 Leaving  the program you don't have to worry about losing any change you may
 have made, since they take effect immediately during normal program usage.

@endnode

@node "ArchiveSettings" "Archive Parameters"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Setting Archive Parameters@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 You  can  modify  at anytime the parameters of the archive currently in use.
 These parameters and the window containing them are of course absolutely the
 same you encounter while Creating a New arhive.

 You  can  freely modify all fields but Archive File Name (easy to guess why)
 and Data Format (both DATE and NUMERICAL).

 For detailed  information  regarding every single parameter please refer to:

 @{"Create New Archive" link "CreaArc" 0}

@endnode

@node "ArchiveInfo" "About Archive"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}About Archive@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  windows  shows  some  useful data about the currently used archive and
 system.  They are listed below:

 The string on the top is the Description of the archive these data refer to.

o @{b}Creation Date
  Creation Time@{ub}
  Date and time of Archive creation.

o @{b}Last Operation at@{ub}
  Date and time of last operation performed on Archive.

o @{b}Records in Archive@{ub}
  TOTAL number of records contained in Archive (including deleted records).

o @{b}Archive Size@{ub}
  Amount  of  disk  space  (in  bytes)  used by the Archive.  This value only
  refers to the file containing actual DATA.

o @{b}Total disk space@{ub}
  Total size (in bytes) of the volume the archive is stored into.

o @{b}Space available on disk@{ub}
  Shows number of free bytes available on the volume containing archive data.

o @{b}Available Memory @{ub}
  Indicates system memory currently available (in bytes).

@endnode

@node "GUISettings" "Configure GUI"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Configure Graphical User Interface@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 Toggles the screen allowing to customize the GUI of the archive currently in
 use.   For every explaination of how to use graphical user archive (GUI) see
 the chapter:

 @{"Graphical Interface" link "SDGUISet.guide/MAIN" 0}

@endnode

@node "DescriptionList" "Description List"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Description List@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This window allows you to insert/modify/delete/sort the list of descriptions
 the  program  is going to use.  All items in this list will then be included
 (in  the  same order) in the list presented whenever you click on the pop-up
 gadget next  to a Description field, in any window it may appear.  That will
 allow you to insert an item with a simple mouse click.

 There  is  no  limit to the number of items this list can contain.  The only
 limit is represented by the memory available on system.

 Selecting OK will store the list in memory and save it to disk, otherwise no
 change will be taken into account.

@endnode

@node "ClassList" "Class List"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Class List@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  window  allows  to  insert/modify/delete/sort  the list of Classes the
 program  is  going to use.  All items in this list will then be included (in
 the  same  order)  in  the  list  presented whenever you click on the pop-up
 gadget  next to a Class field, in any window it may appear.  That will allow
 you to insert an item with a simple mouse click.

 There  is  no  limit to the number of items this list can contain.  The only
 limit is represented by the memory available on system.

 Selecting OK will store the list in memory and save it to disk, otherwise no
 change will be taken into account.

@endnode

@node "AmountList" "Amount List"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Amount List@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  window  allows  to  insert/modify/delete/sort  the list of Amounts the
 program is going to use. All the items in this list will be included (in the
 same  order)  in  the list presented whenever you click on the pop-up gadget
 next  to a Class field, in any window it may appear.  That will allow you to
 insert an item with a simple mouse click.

 There  is  no  limit to the number of items this list can contain.  The only
 limit is represented by the memory available on system.

 Selecting OK will store the list in memory and save it to disk, otherwise no
 change will be taken into account.

 Please  note that  selecting  the  'Sort' gadget causes entries to be sorted
 Alpha-Numerically, not numerically.

@endnode

@node "LoadList" "Load New Lists"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Load New Lists@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  function  is  used  to  load  Description,  Class  and Amount lists by
 selecting a disk file.

 A file requester is shown, where you can select the '@{b}.lst@{ub}' file you
 wish to load.

 When  an  archive  is  created  all  its lists are normally cleared and it's
 necessary  to  type  some  entries to have them available.  But if there are
 other  lists  on  disk (normally belonging to other BancaBase archives) they
 can be loaded thus making them available without having to retype anything.

 BancaBase's  lists  are contained in a single file ending in '@{b}.lst@{ub}'
 so  only  files  with  this extension are shown in this file requester.  The
 program  automatically  recognizes  entries  belonging to different lists by
 using labels.

 Once  the  file  is  successfully loaded the lists only contain new entries.
 Any entry that might have been present before loading has been replaced.

@endnode

@node "DateSort" "Sort by Date"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Sort Records by Date@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 Sorting  records  by  date  is  almost mandatory if you want easier and more
 efficient   handling,   even   many  internal  BancaBase  functions  need  a
 date-sorted archive to work optimally.

 By  selecting  this  function  you  can  have  the  whole archive sorted.  A
 requester asks for confirmation before starting.

 Two different sorting modes are possible:  TURBO mode, which loads the whole
 archive  and  performs  all operation in memory (very fast), and NORMAL mode
 which operates directly on disk and is rather slow.

 The  program  checks  if  enough free memory for TURBO mode is available and
 behave consequentely

 If  TURBO  mode  is  used,  the  sorted  file  is first saved to disk with a
 temporary  name.  Only if this operation has been successful the old file is
 removed and the new one renamed, so this is a safe procedure.

 If  otherwise NORMAL mode is used I suggest not to start other programs that
 may access disk files in order to make the procedure take the shortest time.

 Sort  mode  being  used  is  shown  in the titlebar of the window which also
 contains  a  PROGRESS  BAR  indicating  how much of the job has already been
 done.

@endnode

@node "DeleteAllRecs" "Delete all Data"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Delete all Data@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  function  completely  removes all records from archive.  Related files
 are NOT deleted, only actual records are, so it may be useful if you want to
 rebuild  from  scratch an archive you already have on disk.  For example you
 can  use one of the demo archives provided (thus mantaining all settings and
 preferences)  and selecting this option you can begin your budget management
 starting from record #1.

 To  delete  all  records  you  have  to  confirm  (for security reasons) two
 requesters.

 I  remind you that if you want to manage a Current Account you better insert
 a  certain  *SALDO*  as  first  record,  for  example the one banks normally
 communicate.   This  ensure  that all following operations, which relates to
 the first record, will return the actual value of your current account.

@endnode

@node "AutoRecalc" "Auto Recalculate"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Auto Recalculate Totals@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  menu  enables  or disables the automatic recalculation of balance.  If
 active,  the  program  automatically  recalculates  both  total and filtered
 balance  whenever  you  insert  an operation which modifies them.  Of course
 this option is useless if @{"Show Totals" link "ShowTot"} is not activated as well.

 The first recalculation is run immediately after you toggle it on.

 The status of this switch can be stored together with other archive settings
 via the @{"Archive Parameters" link "ArchiveSettings"} window.

 Any modification of this option via the menu is not stored on disk.

@endnode

@node "ShowTot" "Show Totals"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Show Totals@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  menu  toggles  on and off the display of total and filtered balance in
 the bottom frame of screen.

 The status of this switch can be stored together with other archive settings
 via the @{"Archive Parameters" link "ArchiveSettings"} window.

 Any modification of this option via the menu is not stored on disk.

@endnode

@node "BrowseRec" "Show/Modify Movements"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Show/Modify Movements - Record Browser@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  option  opens  a  window to display a list of all records contained in
 the  archive.   Records  are  displayed  using  colors  as  set  in  archive
 parameters.   The  background  color of the list is instead the same used in
 List Gadgets.

 The  record display window contains some gadget which allow browsing through
 stored records.  Here follows a brief description of all available commands:

 Bottom  gadgets (starting from left):


 |<          Jump to record #1.              (SHIFT LEFT ARROW)

  <          Go back to previous page.       (LEFT ARROW)

  >          Go to next page.                (RIGHT ARROW)

  >|         Jump to last page.              (SHIFT RIGHT ARROW)

 DOWN        Select next record.             (DOWN ARROW)

 UP          Select previous record.         (UP ARROW)

 Modify      Allows editing of currently selected record.

 Erase       Removes currently selected record (confirmation required)

 Quit        Quits Record Browser.

 Display     This shows something like :   A  B : C    Rec: D
             where : A = Total number of records.
                     B = First record displayed.
                     C = Last record displayed.
                     D = Currently selected record.

 Slider      Allows to scroll the entire list.

 You can select records by directly clicking on them.  This leads to two more
 possibilities:

 A double click on the same record with LEFT MOUSE button allows to edit it.

 A  double  click on the same record with RIGHT MOUSE buttom allows to delete
 it (a confirmation is required).

@endnode

@node "InsertRec" "Insert Operation"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Insert Operation@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 In  this  window  you  can insert new records (or operations).  Window title
 indicates the progressive number of current record.

 The Insert Window gadgets:

 @{b}Reference Date@{ub}
 It's  the  operation  date.   The  program  initially sets it to the default
 defined in the program Reference Date field. See also @{"Reference Date" link "RefDate" 0}.

 @{b}Description@{ub}
 This  field  is  used  to  store  operation  description.  The POP-UP gadget
 recalls  the Description List, where you can easily select one of the preset
 descriptions. For more information see also @{"Description List" link "DescriptionList" 0}.

 @{b}Class@{ub}
 Here  you can introduce operation class.  A class is a category which groups
 various  kinds  of operation.  For example it can be the name of a bank, the
 number  of a current account, or something like House Expenses, House Bills,
 Car  Expenses  ecc.  Program  philosophy  is based on classifying operations
 within  the  same  archive in categories, which may be later used to perform
 various  analyses.   A  correct  usage  of  categories is very important.  I
 suggest you to follow the example given by the included archives to get some
 hint.  The POP-UP gadget recalls the Class List, where you can easily select
 one  of  the  preset  classes.  For more information see also @{"Class List" link "ClassList" 0}.

 @{b}Amount@{ub}
 Insert here  the  operation amount.  Only numbers are allowed, no symbols or
 dots.   Decimal  point  is  allowed  only  if  the  two-decimal  fixed point
 numerical  format  is  set.  For this field too is available a POP-UP gadget
 which  automatically recalls the Amount List where you can easily select one
 of the preset amounts. For more details see @{"Amount  List"  link "AmountList" 0}.

 @{b}Sign@{ub}
 The  field  containing  operation sign.  You can type the sign directly into
 the  string gadget, or click on one of the two buttons next to it for a fast
 mouse  insertion.  Only '+', '-' and ' ' (space) are allowed.  Any operation
 having  a  SPACE  as  sign  (thus no sign) is not calculated by the program.
 This  is  useful  because allows you to insert operations whose amounts have
 not  been  drawn  or  paid yet, and so they don't contribute to balance.  As
 soon  as  the amount is drawn or paid you only have to recall the record and
 add its sign to include it in balance.

 @{b}Save@{ub}
 Stores  on  disk the record just inserted, closes the window and reopens it,
 ready for the next insertion.

 @{b}Cancel@{ub}
 Quits  the  insert  function  with  no  change  (just  like the window CLOSE
 gadget does).

 @{b}Display@{ub}
 The  display  constantly  shows  the  number  inserted  in the amount field,
 numerically  formatted in such a way it's easy to read.  This helps avoiding
 trivial  mistakes  when introducing numbers with many zeros.  It's good rule
 to check this display before saving the operation on disk.

 After you insert a new record, if Auto Recalculate is on the program updates
 both  total  and  filtered  balance  and if Show Total is active updates the
 display as well.

@endnode

@node "Grouping" "Selective Collecting"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Selective Collecting@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  function  collects  a  group  of  records in one that represents their
 algebraic  sum.   It  can  be  used to store a long list of operations which
 refer  to  a  past  year,  or  a series  of payments already executed, or in
 general  whenever  you don't need to keep track of each movement but you can
 sum up their amounts in just one record.

 As  first  you  will  be  presented with a window that allows you to set the
 filters  the  program  is  going  to use to select the desired records.  For
 further details see also @{"Filter Settings" link "FilterSettings" 0}.

 After  this  operation,  the  program  will  open  a  requester  and ask for
 confirmation.   If  you  didn't  set  filters  correctly  or  set  them  too
 generically, the requester will report this in its message.

 After  that,  a  window  is  open, displaying a PROGRESS BAR which shows the
 advancement  status of the process, while the lower frame indicates how many
 records  satisfy  the  conditions  set  by filters and are thus selected for
 collecting.

 This  ends  the  first  phase,  and  you  will  be  given the opportunity to
 display  all  records  collected  in a table.  This is for two main reasons:
 you  can  verify  by yourself that the program didn't include some important
 record,  and  you  can print the whole table in order to enclose it with the
 rest of the paper documentation of your personal balance.

 Now a requester will ask you if you really intend to delete all the selected
 (and displayed) records or cancel the operation.

 In the former case all selected records are deleted from the Archive, then a
 new one is created with the current (system) date and the string "Collecting
 of  (N)  data"  in  the  Class  field,  where (N) is the number of collected
 records.   The  Amount  field  contains  the  algebraic  sum  of the records
 affected  by  the  operation.  A requester asks if now you want to edit this
 new record to set its fields in some more convenient way, otherwise you will
 be able to edit it later just like the others.

 In  case you prefer to cancel this operation the program will simply restore
 all marked records.

 Both  phases  (restoring  or  collecting) are commented in the window by the
 PROGRESS  BAR  and  by the number of collected records, which, in the latter
 case, will approach zero.

@endnode


@node "FilterSettings" "Set Filters ..."
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Set Filters@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 Filters  are  used  to determine the "scope" some function are bound to work
 in.   For  example,  all  functions  for  balance computation, or for record
 collecting, or the statistical ones.

 The filter settings window is full of gadgets which allow total control over
 them. Here is a detailed description:


 @{b}From Day@{ub}
 Sets  the  starting date.  All records whose date is former than the one set
 here will not be included by filter.  The POP-UP gadget allows an easier and
 more immediate selection of date.


 @{b}F@{ub}
 Clicking  on  this  gadget will cause the program to automatically fetch the
 date  contained  in the first record in archive, just saving you the time to
 look for it.

 @{b}To Day@{ub}
 Sets the date starting from which no record should be inluded by filter.

 @{b}L@{ub}
 This  gadget  tells  the  program  to fetch the data contained into the last
 record in archive and paste it into the 'To Day' field.

 @{b}Class@{ub}
 Indicates  the  class  records  should  belong to in order to be included by
 filter.  You can enter some characters only, for example:

 If you enter :

 @{u}Expense@{uu}

 all  records  whose  class  string  starts  with  'Expense' will be accepted by
 filter.  For example :

 Expense  HOUSE    Accepted
 Expense  CAR      Accepted
 Expense           Accepted
 Equipment         Refused

 You  can  use  wildcards  as  well,  like the asterisk, in order to make the
 search more flexible.  Example:

 Entering  'Expense C*' in the Class field, all the following records will be
 accepted:

 Expense CAR         Accepted
 Expense CAR TAXES   Accepted
 Expense CAT         Accepted
 Expense TAXES       Refused

 The  POP-UP gadget allows a quick selection of preset classes, as entered in
 the @{"Class List" link "ClassList" 0}.

 If this field is left blank, any Class will be accepted.

 @{b}Segno@{ub}
 You  can  also  indicate the sign of operation being included by the filter.
 Entering a '+', only operations with this sign will be selected.

 @{b}Description@{ub}
 The  description  records must have in order to be included by filter.  Here
 too  you can enter part of the string only, or use the special character, as
 in  the  Class  field.   If  you  leave  it  blank, all Descriptions will be
 accepted   by  filter.   The  POP-UP  gadget  allows  to  quickly  select  a
 Description included in the @{"Description List" link "DescriptionList" 0}.

 @{b}Calculate balance as first record@{ub}
 If  active  this  gadget  tells the program to calculate the balance for all
 records whose date is former with respect of the one set as Starting Date.

 For  example,  if  you  want  a  table showing the balance of the last month
 (let's  assume  January, 1997), you set a filter which selects all operation
 between  01/01/1997 and 01/31/1997.  If  you don't activate this gadget, the
 displayed  total  will be the algebraic sum of all January movements, thus a
 partial  balance  of  the considered month.  But if you activate this switch
 istead,  a  balance  referring  to  the  day  before  the  starting  date is
 calculated  and included as first record.  So this time a real total balance
 at the end of the month is shown.

 @{b}Recall@{ub}
 Allows  to  recall the last saved filter settings.  These inlude 'From Day',
 'To Day', 'Class', 'Sign' and 'Desription' fields.

 @{b}Save@{ub}
 Saves  current  filter  settings  on  disk.   It saves 'From Day', 'To Day',
 'Class',  'Sign'  and  'Desription'  fields.  When an archive is loaded, the
 program also loads its filter profile as saved by this function.

 @{b}Use these filters@{ub}
 With  this  gadget  the current settings are accepted.  The program will use
 them  whenever  required  in  an operation.  Filtered Balance is recalculatd
 using current filter profile as well.

 @{b}Cancel@{ub}
 Cancels all modifications and restores previous values.

@endnode

@node "Export" "Export"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Export@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 Using  this  function  you  can export data contained in the archive into an
 ASCII  file.   This  file  can  be  formatted  in  order to be recognised by
 programs other than BancaBase itself.

 The export windows has the following gadgets:

 @{b}File Name@{ub}
 Here  you have to type the name (with path) of the file the program is going
 to  generate.   For  a quick path or device selection you can use the POP-UP
 gadget, which automatically recalls a system file requester.

 @{b}File contains record headers@{ub}
 Ticking  this  gadget  tells  the  program to save record field names in the
 first line of the generated file.

 @{b}Format@{ub}
 This  cycle  gadget  contains  a  list  of presets for the programs directly
 supported by BancaBase.  Presets are available for the following programs:

 @{fg highlight}BancaBase, TurboCalc, SuperBase and Digita Datastore@{fg text}

 If  you  choose a Preset Format the program automatically sets all paramters
 accordingly,  so  that  a  suitable file is created.  There is also a Custom
 format you can use to set your own desired combination.

 The  generated  data  type  is  @{b}@{u}ASCII CSV@{ub}@{uu}, thus compatible with all programs
 supporting this format.

 @{b}Field Separator@{ub}
 Allows  to  choose  the SEPARATING CHARACTER the program will insert between
 fields.

 @{b}Record Separator@{ub}
 Allows  to  choose the SEPARATING CHARACTER the programm will insert between
 records.

 @{b}Export@{ub}
 When  you  click on this gadget all parameters will be accepted and you will
 be  presented  with  the Filter Settings window, where you can specify which
 records   to   export.    For   further   details   see  the  section  about
 @{"Filter Settings" link "FilterSettings"0}.

 To proceed with exporting you have to confirm the Filters window as well.

 If  the  chosen file already exists, the program will ask for a confirmation
 before  overwriting  it.   Once  the operation is completed a requester will
 show the number of exported records.

 @{b}Cancel@{ub}
 This gadget cancels the operation.

@endnode

@node "Import" "Import"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Import@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  function  makes  possible  to  import  records  from file generated by
 BancaBase (or other programs).

 Parameters, their functions and the rules to follow to set them properly are
 identical to those described in the @{"Export" link "Export" 0} section.

 You  have  to  select  the  name of the file containing the data you wish to
 import  and  set  the parameters accordingly to the file format, so that the
 program is able to correctly handle that file.

 Of  course  you  have  to know the format of the data being imported. Future
 versions will include an algorithm for automatic file recognition.

 Clicking on IMPORT the program perform the following tests:

 o  It  checks  whether  the  file  format  is   correct.  Then the number of
    recognized fields and the number or records.

 o  It  calculates  the  space needed on data disk to store the records being
    imported, and compares it to the available space.

 If  everything  is  fine  it  displays those data in a requester, asking for
 confirmation.   After that another window is open, containing a PROGRESS BAR
 you can use to follow the progress of the import operation.

 Once  completed,  the  program  will  recalculate  the totals and update its
 internal variables.

@endnode

@node "RestoreRecs" "Restore Records"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Restore Records@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  function  allows to restore records possibly deleted from the archive.
 Thanks  to  BancaBase's  use  of  FLAGS, deleted or collected records may be
 restored.

 @{b}@{u}Warning :@{uu}
 Only  records  deleted  by  the  Collecting  function and those removed from
 Record Browser can be recovered.
 @{ub}

 If some recoverable records are present, their number will be displayed in a
 requester that you have to confirm before proceeding.

 A  window  will  display  a PROGRESS BAR showing the advancing status of the
 operation.

@endnode

@node "PurgeRecs" "Pack/Optimize Records"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Pack/Optimize Records@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 During  normal  usage  of  an archive you usually insert new records, delete
 some   of  them  and  collect  some  others.   This  causes  a  non  uniform
 distribution  of  active  records  inside the data file and consequently all
 read/write operation will slow down.

 This function perform the mantainance necessary to avoid that problem.

 Firstly  the  program  checks  whether  the  archive  actually  needs  to be
 optimized.  If that is the case a confirmation requester is open.

 If  you  continue,  a  window  containing  a  PROGRESS  BAR will display the
 proceeding status of the operation.

 This  function works safely.  A temporary file is created, where only active
 records  are  saved.   Once  the  operation  has  successfully completed the
 program deletes the old file and renames the one just created.

 Once completed you will be able to resume your work.

 @{B}NOTE@{ub}
 After  this function no previously deleted record will be recoverable, since
 they will be effectively removed from the archive.

 See also @{"Restore Records" link "RestoreRecs" 0}.

@endnode

@node "ShowBalance" "Show Statement of Account"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Show Statement of Account@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 To  compute  and display the Statement of Account you can use this function,
 too.  It works exactly like the other functions that calculate the Statement
 of  Account,  the  only  difference  being that this one doesn't produce any
 table but simply displays the result in a window.

 Firstly the  @{"Set Filters" link "FilterSettings"} window is opened.

 Then,  after  the  computation, another window will show the total value and
 the number of considered operations.

 If  Show  Total and Auto Recalculate are active, this value must be equal to
 the one displayed in the bottom frame into the "Filtered Total" field.

@endnode

@node "ReportBalance" "Normal Statement of Account"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Normal Statement of Account@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  function  works  exactly  like  the previous one, but also generates a
 report containing all records included into computation.

 For further details see also @{"Show Statement of Account" link "ShowBalance" 0}.

 The report  will be displayed using the chosen Ascii external viewer, or the
 internal viewer @{"SDMore" link "SDGUISet.guide/SDMore" 0}.

 The displayed report can then be scrolled, examined and/or printed.

 For parameters and table format see also @{"Reports Preferences" link "ReportsPrefs"}.

@endnode

@node "InExBalance" "Income/Expense Statement of Account"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Income/Expense Statement of Account@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  function produces a report containing all records matching the defined
 filter,  with Incomes and Expenses in two separated columns.  This makes the
 report easier to read.

 The report  will be displayed using the chosen Ascii external viewer, or the
 internal viewer @{"SDMore" link "SDGUISet.guide/SDMore" 0}.

 The displayed report can then be scrolled, examined and/or printed.

 For parameters and table format see also @{"Reports Preferences" link "ReportsPrefs"}.

@endnode

@node "MonthlyBalance" "Monthly Statement of Account"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Monthly Statement of Account@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  function produces a report containing all records matching the defined
 filter, explicitly showing the monthly balance after the last  operation  of
 each month.

 This  simplifies comparisons with forms provided by the Banks, which usually
 report the balance at the previous month.

 Besides, you can see the trend of your balance month by month.

 After  selecting  this  function, you have to define the filters first, thus
 telling  the  program  to  include into computation only the records you are
 interested in.

 Once the filters are confirmed, the program proceeds with computation of the
 report, showing a window with a PROGRESS BAR during the operation.

 The report  will be displayed using the chosen Ascii external viewer, or the
 internal viewer @{"SDMore" link "SDGUISet.guide/SDMore" 0}.

 The displayed report can then be scrolled, examined and/or printed.

 For parameters and table format see also @{"Reports Preferences" link "ReportsPrefs"}.

@endnode

@node "BNKReport" "Bank Card operations report"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Bank Card operations report@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This function produces a report showing all Bank-Card operations made in the
 Year and Month you specify using a special requester.

 This function recalls a requester into  which  you  can  comfortably  select
 the  Month and Year to be reported.  After confirmation another requester is
 shown, which  you can use to select a Class (it can be the name of a bank, a
 current  account number).  Leaving this field blank will tell the program to
 take  all classes into account.  After that the program will parse the whole
 archive,  searching for Bank-card operations:  they are located when a match
 occurs between the contents of a Class field and the string named "Bank Card
 String", as defined in the archive settings.

 See also @{"Archive Parameters" link "ArchiveSettings" 0}.

 The  report  will  contain  possible  Bank Card operations together with the
 monthly  remaining  withdraw  limit.   This value is calculated from archive
 settings too.

 The report  will be displayed using the chosen Ascii external viewer, or the
 internal viewer @{"SDMore" link "SDGUISet.guide/SDMore" 0}.

 The displayed report can then be scrolled, examined and/or printed.

 For parameters and table format see also @{"Reports Preferences" link "ReportsPrefs"}.

@endnode

@node "CDCReport" "Credit Card operations report"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Credit Card operations report@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  function  produces  a report showing all Credit Card operation made in
 the Year and Month you specify using a special requester.

 The  procedure  and  usage  are  identical to those described in the section
 regarding @{"Bank Card operations report" link "BNKReport" 0}.

@endnode

@node "ReportPrefs" "Listings Preferences"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Listings Preferences@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 Using  this function you can set/edit the parameters affecting the format of
 the reports produced by other functions.

 These are the editable settings:

 @{b}Lines on report sheet@{ub}
 It's the maximum number of lines per page the program is going to output.

 @{b}Put Form Feed in each Page@{ub}
 If  active,  the  program  inserts  a  Form Feed at the end of each page (it
 causes the printer to expel the sheet).


 @{b}Print Archive Description@{ub}
 If  active,  the  title of the archive the report refers to is printed below
 the header.  Title is horizontally centered automatically.

 @{b}Ok@{ub}
 Current  values will be used, but not saved on disk:  they will be lost when
 closing the archive.

 @{b}Save on Disk@{ub}
 Current values are stored together with other Archive parameters directly on
 disk.  They will be loaded and used each time you load the archive.

 @{b}Cancel@{ub}
 Restores previous settings.

 This is how a report is formatted:

 First line:

 Currente DATE   (Function which generates the report)   Pag.xxxx

 Second line : (only if Print Description is active)

                      (Archive Description) <- centered
 at the bottom:

 (a line containing the LINES CHARACTERS as set in the GUI preferences)

 If active, a Form Feed is added.

@endnode

@node "Recalc" "Re-calculate Totals"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Re-calculate Totals@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  functions  forces  the  program  to  recalculate the TOTALS, therefore
 filtered and total balance, and then display them in the frame at the bottom
 of the screen (if show total is active).

 If Auto recalculate is not active, you have to call this functions to update
 the  balance  and  make  sure  the  displayed  data  take  into  account any
 modification you had possibly made.

 During  the  calculation  a  window  containing a PROGRESS BAR is displayed,
 indicating the fraction of the job already completed.

@endnode

@node "AnnualBalance" "Annual Trend Chart"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Annual Trend@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  function produces a three-dimensional chart showing the month-by-month
 situation of the chosen year.

 As  usual, firstly you have to set the filters the program will use for this
 chart.  See also @{"Set Filters" link "FilterSettings"}.

 After that, you choose via a requester the year whose trend you wish to have
 displayed.

 If  you  continue, after some processing a window is open with 12 gadgets in
 it,   each   representing   a   month  of  the  year  and  surmounted  by  a
 three-dimensional  column.  The  color  of  this  column  is  the one set as
 records  color.  If the represented value is positive the color will be that
 of Incomes, otherwise that of Expenses.

 Clicking  on one of the 12 gadget you will be able to see the exact value of
 the  corresponding  three-dimensional bar in the frame below.  This value is
 the  (filtered)  balance of the month only, without considering the previous
 history.

 This  kind  of  chart  is  useful  because  allows to easily evaluate if the
 selected  month  has  been  positive  or negative for balance.  Furthermore,
 since  all months of the selected year are displayed together, only a glance
 is  needed  to  tell  during  which months you spent or managed to save more
 money.

 The  three-dimensional  columns represent the calculated values in scale, so
 they indicate correct proportions among real values.

 To obtain a chart taking into account actual balance as well you have to use
 the @{"Annual/Monthly Histogram" link "AnnualGraph" 0} function.

@endnode

@node "AnnualGraph" "Annual/Monthly Histogram"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Annual/Monthly Histogram@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  function draws a three-dimensional chart representing the actual trend
 of your own balance, with relative totals.

 As usual, first you have to define the filters the program is going  to  use
 for this chart.  See also @{"Set Filters" link "FilterSettings"}.

 After  that,  you will have to select via a requester which year you want to
 be analyzed and the results plotted.

 Once  the  computation  is  completed,  the program opens a window with a 3D
 chart in it, showing in a fixed scale the trend of the whole selected year.

 The horizontal axis has the 12 months indicated, or the days of the selected
 month,  while  on  the vertical axis there are the values represented in the
 chart.

 The  subdivision  of  the horizontal axis is worth a better examination.  In
 the  annual  representation the ruler is divided into 12 parts (one for each
 month),  while  in the one-month display it is divided into as many sections
 as the days of the considered month, with more evident ticks every 10.

 Instead, the vertical axis shows four values, which are:

 o  The  balance,  referred to the first day displayed in the chart.  In the
    annual chart it is referred to January, 1st of the year being considered.

 o  The Maximum value reached by the chart in the current display.

 o  The Minimum value reached by the chart in the current display.

 o  The balance, referred to the last day displayed in the chart.

The gadgets of the window :

 @{b}Whole year@{ub}
 Goes back to the whole-year display.

 @{b}Print Chart@{ub}
 Allows  to  GRAPHICALLY  print  the  whole  3d  chart.   A  request  ask for
 confirmation  before  proceeding, then you can select the graphic resolution
 (and  thus  the  print  quality)  to  print  with in another requester.  The
 higher the chosen number, the best the resolution obtained at the price of a
 longer  printing time.  During  this phase a requester is shown which allows
 to stop the printing process whenever you want.

 @{b}Select Month@{ub}
 This  gadget opens a requester where you can select the desired month.  Then
 the monthly detailed chart will be displayed.

 Note  that  the window title always indicate what the currently viewed chart
 refers to:  in case of monthly chart both year and month are shown.

 @{b}To Exit@{ub}
 Click on window's CLOSE gadget or press ESC.

@endnode

@node "DayDiff" "Day Difference Calculation"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Day Difference@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  utility  allow to quickly calculate the difference in days between two
 dates.

 @{b}Beginning Date@{ub}
 Indicate here the date to start counting days from (earlier date).

 @{b}Ending Date@{ub}
 Indicate  here  the  reference  date  the  calculation should stop at (later
 date).

 @{b}Display@{ub}
 Constantly shows the result of the difference between the dates set above.

 You  can  comfortably  and  quickly  choose  the  dates  using  the provided
 requester, called by clicking on the POP-UP gadget.

@endnode

@node "DaySum" "Day Sum Calculation"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Day Sum@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  utility calculates the date resulting by adding or subtracting a given
 number of days from another date.

 It  can  be useful  to know for example the expiring date of a payment given
 the number of days left.

 @{b}Starting Date@{ub}
 Enter here the date to start the calculation from.

 @{b}Number of days@{ub}
 Number  of days between -20,000 and +20,000 to algebraically add to the date
 set above.

 @{b}Display@{ub}
 Constantly shows the date resulting from the operation.

 Date  and  number  can  be  comfortably  and  quickly  selected by using the
 provided requester, which can be recalled clicking on the POP-UP gadgets.

@endnode

@node "Calculator" "Calculator"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Calculator@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  menu  recalls  the  system Calculator on BancaBase's screen.  The only
 rule  is  that  the  Calculator  executable must be in the same directory of
 BancaBase itself.

 The Calculator can remain active while you continue using BancaBase, it must
 be  closed  only  before leaving the program and whenever the program itself
 explicitly requires that.

@endnode

@node "Help" "Main Help"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Main Help@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 Opens this AmigaGuide document on BancaBase's screen.

 The  manual may stay open on the screen:  the program will close it whenever
 required.

@endnode

@node "FunctionsHelp" "Functions Help"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Help about Functions@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 Opens  this  AmigaGuide document on BancaBase's screen, directly showing the
 section containing the list of available functions.

 The  manual may stay open on the screen:  the program will close it whenever
 required.

@endnode

@node "IconTools" "Icon Tooltypes"
@prev "BBFunctions"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Icon Tooltypes@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 Many program settings can be specified by using Icon Tooltypes.

 The  same  parameters  listed  below  can be passed via CLI if you start the
 program that way.

 @{b}DATA_FILE=@{ub}
 It's  the  default archive or directory used in the File Requester open when
 you select @{"Load Archive" link "LoadArc"}.

 @{b}PREFS_FILE=@{ub}
 The  name  of  the  graphical  preference  file  the  program must load when
 started.  In none is specified the default graphical settings are used.

 @{b}HELP_FILE=@{ub}
 The  name (with path) of the file the program must load when ON-LINE HELP is
 activated. Its default is  @{u}Docs/BancaBase.guide@{uu}.  If  the  selected
 name is not correct the program won't be able to use on-line help.

 @{b}MACROFILE=@{ub}
 The  name of the file containing the FUNCTION KEYS configuration the program
 must load when started.

 @{b}PAPER_HEIGHT=@{ub}
 Indicate  here  the  number of lines per page (for reports) the program must
 use as a default when creating a new archive.

 @{b}TURBO_SORT=@{ub}
 Toggles  the  TURBO  archive  sorting mode on/off.  Allowed values are ON to
 switch  this  function  on, OFF to switch it off.  By default the sorting is
 performed  in  TURBO  mode,  since the program itself can automatically fall
 back to normal mode if the necessary conditions are not met.

 @{b}BNK_STR=@{ub}
 Indicate  here  the  string  the program must use as a default value for the
 Bank Card String field when creating a new archive. See @{"Create New Archive" link "CreaArc" 0}
 for further details.

 @{b}BNK_MAX=@{ub}
 Insert  here  the MAXIMUM monthly limit for expenses made with Bank Card. No
 spaces or separating character are allowed, only the amount.

 @{b}CDC_STR=@{ub}
 Indicate  here  the  string  the program must use as a default value for the
 Credit Card String field when creating a new archive. See @{"Create New Archive" link "CreaArc" 0}
 for further details.

 @{b}CDC_MAX=@{ub}
 Insert here the MAXIMUM monthly limit for expenses made with Credit Card. No
 spaces or separating character are allow, only the amount.

 @{b}SCREEN_BAR=@{ub}
 Sets  the  starting status of the program SCREEN BAR.  Allowed values are ON
 to activate the BAR, OFF to deactivate it.

 @{b}CURRENCY=@{ub}
 Insert  here the name of the currency the program must use as a default when
 creating a new archive.  This string can be maximum 4 characters long.

 @{b}LANGUAGE=@{ub}
 Forces the program to load the catalog file of the language you insert here.
 This  file  must be either in the catalogs/ directory of BancaBase or in the
 system  LOCALE:   assignment.   If the chosen language is not available, the
 deafault one is used instead.

@endnode
